      <body>

         <head rend="center"><title type="main">Song<emph rend="super">1</emph><note type="head"
                  place="bottom"><emph rend="super">1</emph> From a letter of Robert Burns to George
                  Thomson, October 29, 1793. First published in James Currie's <emph rend="italic"
                     >Works of Robert Burns</emph>, 4 vols. (Liverpool: M'Creery, 1800), IV:
                  pp. 140-141.</note></title></head>
        
         <lg type="stanza">
            <l>O condescend, dear, charming maid,</l>
            <l rend="indent">My wretched state to view;</l>
            <l>A tender swain to love betray’d,</l>
            <l rend="indent">And sad despair by you.</l>
         </lg>

         <lg type="stanza">
            <l n="5">While here, all melancholy,</l>
            <l rend="indent">My passion I deplore,</l>
            <l>Yet, urged by stern resistless fate,</l>
            <l rend="indent">I love thee more and more.</l>
         </lg>

         <lg type="stanza">
            <l>I heard of love, and with disdain</l>
            <l n="10" rend="indent">The urchin’s power denied;</l>
            <l>I laugh’d at every lover’s pain,</l>
            <l rend="indent">And mock’d them when they sigh’d.</l>
         </lg>

         <lg type="stanza">
            <l>But how my state is alter’d!</l>
            <l rend="indent">Those happy days are o’er;</l>
            <l n="15">For all thy unrelenting hate,</l>
            <l rend="indent">I love thee more and more</l>
         </lg>

         <lg type="stanza">
            <l>O yield, illustrious beauty, yield,</l>
            <l rend="indent">No longer let me mourn;</l>
            <l>And though victorious in the field,</l>
            <l n="20" rend="indent">Thy captive do not scorn.</l>
         </lg>

         <lg type="stanza">
            <l>Let generous pity warm thee,</l>
            <l rend="indent">My wonted peace restore;</l>
            <l>And, grateful, I shall bless thee still,</l>
            <l rend="indent">And love thee more and more.</l>
         </lg>

      </body>
